notes.body:
Losartan body model
losartan and exp3174 are excreted in urine; urinary excretion of losartan and exp3174, but low recoveries (~5% losartan, 6% exp3174 [Yasar2002a])
IV losartan [FDA]:
urine
total metabolites: 43.3 ± 8.4 % (urine);
losartan: 11.4 ± 4.0 % (urine)
e3174: 6.44 ± 2.45 % (urine)
other: 17.6 % (urine)
feces
total metabolites: 49.5 ± 13.3 % (feces);
losartan: 7.77 - 12.8 % (urine)
e3174: 6.92 - 13.38 % (urine)
other: ~16% (urine)
fast halflife of losartan (removal plasma in ~12hr) => no accumlation expected in multiple dosing
longer halflife, slower peaks of exp3174 (removal plasma in ~24hr) => accumulation
33-35 % bioavailability; 38.9 ± 14.7% [Lo1995]
55% of infused EXP3174 is recovered in urine; probably metabolization of the metabolite (in liver?) [Lo1995]

Organic Anion Transporting Polypeptide 2B1 (OATP2B1): Recent findings suggest that losartan is also a substrate for OATP2B1, a transporter that plays a crucial role in the uptake of various drugs into hepatocytes. This transporter facilitates the entry of losartan into liver cells, where it can be metabolized by cytochrome P450 enzymes. [perplexity]
Likely catalyzed CYP2C9 and CYP3A4. Currently only modified via CYP2C9 factor.
Formation of losartan glucuronides, likely via UGT enzymes.
Import via OATP2B1 is irreversible at apical membrane of enterocytes.
Efflux is catalyzed by P-glycoprotein.
Swallowing, dissolution of tablet, and transport into intestine. Overall process describing the rates of this processes.
